\begin_layout Standard
Two changes seem worth discussion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Frequently used constants should be isolated in one location and referenced
 by all calculations that use them.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Derived constants would be better stated in derived form so that, if one
 of the fundamental numbers changes, all will change.
 For example, the gas constant for dry air 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{d}=R_{0}/M_{w}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the universal gas constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{w}$
\end_inset

 is the molecular weight of water.
 It is better to use the quotient of the two values instead of a numerical
 value for 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{d}$
\end_inset

 to ensure consistency and to avoid the problem that the code now has a
 variety of different values in use for 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{d}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A section of the documentation can then provide the fundamental constants
 used and the values, along with documentation when those change.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
More attention to units seems worthwhile.
 Now the code is a mixture of MKS and CGS with occasional other units like
 Calories or knots.
 It would be fairly simple to move to an MKS system of units and to introduce
 global conversion factors where necessary: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ckg2g=1000.
 [g/kg]
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to convert from kg to g, Cmb2Pa=100.
 [Pa/hPa] to convert from mb to Pa, Cdeg2km=111.12 [km/deg latitude] to convert
 from latitude to km, etc.
 This would make the code more readable and would ensure that units in equations
 can be checked.
 (A good example of the confusion that arises otherwise is in the code for
 the King probe, where the equation seems to omit the specific heat of water
 but is nevertheless correct because the specific heat in the units being
 used is 1 cal/g so was just omitted from the equation.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More specific recommendations are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Change the Stephan-Boltzmann constant from 5.6686
\begin_inset Formula $\times10^{-8}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $5.6704\times10^{-8}$
\end_inset

 to match current NIST recommendations.
 Also change the name used in Bulletin 9, where it is now called the Boltzmann
 constant.
 That is a different constant with a very different value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Change the conversion from degrees latitude to km to be 111.12 (not 111.17
 as at present).
 The value 111.12 is exact by definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Occasionally, in Bulletin 9, there is reference to the constant 273.16 as
 the conversion from Celsium to Kelvin; the correct conversion is 273.15,
 so references to 273.16 should be changed unless they refer to the triple
 point of water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Occasionally the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{d}/c_{pd}$
\end_inset

 is taken to be exactly 2/7; in other places a numerical value is used,
 sometimes equal to 2/7 rounded, sometimes different, and separate values
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{pd}$
\end_inset

 are used without regard to the ratio to 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{d}$
\end_inset

.
 This should all be made consistent.
\end_layout

